Explanations for global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report (Global Competitiveness Report) for the year 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada took the top three places, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe formed the bottom end.
(All ranking lists can be read at www.weforum.com .)
As a co-responsible leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there a competition among countries, in addition to the military one, that is also economic in nature?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined precisely: that is, the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth in the medium term – that is, in a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of a country simultaneously says something about the missing competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on earth could simultaneously achieve a higher growth rate.
Despite this, it is sensible to create a ranking list of countries in terms of their growth capacity.
Each country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions are able to keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some respects, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries, for example, compete for internationally mobile capital.
The more a country can win in foreign direct investments, the less another country gets.
This becomes clear when countries bid on a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor factory, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce and often even tax benefits, improved infrastructure and even study plan adjustments at the local technical university are used as a bargaining chip.
This year, we determined the competitiveness (growth potential) of a country based on three broad criteria: (1) technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated indices, whose average values were calculated using a specific method to then create a general growth and competitiveness index.
Technology criterion refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and apply technologies that have been developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the US, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development, thereby achieving high values in the innovation field.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore also achieve little in terms of new products and procedures.
Innovative countries also enjoy a high standard of living due to these innovations.
In this field, the US, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three places on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can one trust that the government complies with its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and rotten judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are world leaders and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also at the top of the rankings.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced state budget, a realistic exchange rate for the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to obtain loans on the capital market and high trust that the government will meet its financial obligations.
From the example of Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can render economic growth ineffective, even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the global economy can be divided into two categories of countries: innovative and non-innovative.
About 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, an excellent system of technological innovations is considered a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
The universities must be excellent, state laboratories should have world-class levels, and the government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing compulsory schooling.
In the US and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is equally important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed in the country itself.
Some countries are good at importing new technologies, while others are less so.
In the past ten or fifteen years, most technology imports occurred within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies, which increased the efficiency of production in the respective target country's economy.
Therefore, it was sensible for the respective countries to make every effort to attract these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of the competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that rank first this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others, ranking further down, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Partially, the slowdown of the economy is connected to the terror attacks on 11 September, but it also becomes increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already slipping into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the USA will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
